segments.text: Okay, we're taping again.
This is the guy that's the union representative to SEIU.
He doesn't work for librarians, he does work for the library, but represents several different guilds, one of them being the librarians' guild.
And he stood up at one place and suggested, well, just, you know,
As you've got to cut things, reduce your book budget.
And my position was absolutely not.
Why do people come to a library?
Do they come to a library to see staff, or do they come to a library for books and materials?
What do you change the nature of the institution?
This is the argument we had in 1994, when the proposal of the mayor was basically to eliminate the book budget.
You change the nature of an institution if you're no longer buying materials.
Are you buying materials now?
I mean, I've heard suggestions that new acquisitions of books is almost moribund right now.
Is that...?
I don't think that's true.
No, no, that's something I'll ask.
Let me be really honest, too.
I think that some of the people you're talking to, I think, are some of the most deceitful group of people with their own political agenda.
I think the agenda of about five of the library staff, and you've probably talked to all five, or you will, has been maintaining their own political power, has been
I mean, even Dowlin, going to his teaching job he's got now, was hounded.
David Price, who was our financial guy, was hounded in his job as a state librarian in West Virginia.
Do you want to see how great these folks are?
Would you like to see?
This is up on billboards, you know, around, went up this weekend.
This is on me.
I want to post that.
I'm looking for the take at a wanted post to Stephen A. Coulter, SBC Communications.
What's that, SBC Communications?
It's the Holman Company.
I'm sorry, Bill.
So this is what you are.
You represent the public, not a greedy Texas telephone company.
You're a lawbreaker, a public library.
What do they mean by that?
They're alleging that you're a lawbreaker?
A legal conflict?
Coulter owns over 5,000 SBCs?
If it's true, why is it an issue?
I didn't put it up.
No one has come and talked to me about it.
Yeah, legal meetings.
Open meetings.
Are they alleging open meeting law violations?
How do you respond when you see something like this?
Because I just laughed.
I couldn't believe it.
I've gotten several calls today.
Why is there this kind of hostility?
Is this coming from this group of librarians?
a guy named Gillespie, who's in court suing us on stuff, and some of the people you're going to be talking to tomorrow you've already talked to.

It's the guild activists of which they're—some of the guild stewards, frankly, are fine and great people, but there's two or three that have a really sour attitude on life, and they don't want any changes, no matter what the changes are.
Wax eloquently about the glories of the old main library, you know, when it was a disaster.
And this kind of stuff.
I mean, I get attacked at commission meetings fairly regularly by guild people, and by half a dozen, not even half a dozen, three or four, that the gadflies, two or three of them more than most.
What do you mean gadflies?
These are people from the civilian side of speech.
Yeah, they're just self-appointed community people who come in, and there's about four of them.
Like Kerwin?
is one of those that's involved in a lawsuit that Jim Gillespie you will end up talking to.
Chafee.
Chafee's fame and glory is that he hasn't missed a commission meeting in 20 years.
He alleges that there was money left for acquisitions of books and that it was diverted to
to get computer stuff.
And I guess there wasn't one of the suits that you watched, I think, by the way.
You suit us on that.

The suit that's in court right now, in which that's where this tape issue comes up, is whether under the Sunshine Ordinance we came out of a closed-door session and announced that we had a leading candidate for secretary.
We would not announce it yet pending a background investigation by staff.
and further questions by a couple of us of some of his previous employers.
They sued over that and the appointment of Gina Menudry, but this is the one that's still there.
The judge ruled that Gina Menudry was moot, and it was the mayor's prerogative.
She sounds wonderful.
Oh, she's wonderful.
I can't wait to meet her.
She's a hoot.
Wasn't she considered for the Dowling job?
Wasn't she actually considered for this job once upon a time?
She told me that, yeah.
I wasn't here when Dalvin was.
This was before my watch.
Dalvin was hired in 87.
I came on at the end of the day.
But anyway, so they're in suit.
They try to get a restraining order against us for moving forward.
And it gets really vicious.
The tape of that particular meeting, we can't find.
But the legal issue is minuscule, basically, as to whether or not we had to

Their position is we have to violate the privacy of the individual candidate because we said we had a leading contender, therefore we had to go public with that, and then do the background search with the police search.
We talked to previous employers.
We told staff to do that.
The next meeting of the commission, we heard from the staff on the background.
We interviewed the guy once more.
We offered him a job.
We came out and we announced.
They're claiming that we are criminals because
of how we handled that.
This is Chafee's 15th lawsuit against us.
He won one.
The one that he won was three committee members were meeting.
There were seven members on the commission.
Three people were sitting holding a meeting on finance, and one of the commissioners came, another commissioner came and sat in the audience and wanted to hear the testimony.
They claimed that that was an illegal meeting of the Library Commission because you had a fourth member there, even if she didn't say it.
She just sat, listened, took some notes, got up a month.
They're claiming that that was a violation.
And the judge said, under the Sunshine Ordinance, technically that's true.
So going forward, if, for example, what came up not a month later was I wanted to testify on my own bill that I had up in front of the commissions.
And so we had to post a legal notice that said this is a meeting of the planning committee, you know, composed of these people.
If a fourth commissioner should attend, it will become a full meeting of the library commission and is duly noticed, which is absurd and it's very confusing.
I showed up at the meeting, presented to the committee, left.
They then went into courts.
accused me of blatantly disregarding the judge's orders and accused me of criminal conduct, and the judge threw it out.
Said what they did was perfectly reasonable.
They followed precisely what it was I suggested.
That's the level of combat.
I call it fairies on it, counting fairies on the head of the pin, kind of legalese.
I mean, if you think of in the...
In the Middle Ages.
There's angels on the head of a pin, yeah.
Yeah, angels on the head of a pin are fairies.
It is, it's nonsensical, the stuff we get into.
But you get this stuff, the judge actually lost his temper with them last week at one of their court events.
So what's motivating the gadflies?
The gadflies, oh, it's fame and glory.
I mean, it's trying to, it's a gotcha game.
I mean, you think it's a substitute for there's no more Vietnam War or something like that?
I mean, you think these are people who are inclined to— These are people who are looking— They're in San Francisco.
They're looking for evil, and they will find it.
Chaffey was quite honest in one of his presentations to it.
He doesn't talk often, but he's been doing it for the last few months.
Because for basically two years, he would never say a thing.
But he would write these scathing things and be quoted in The Independent or The Guardian, two or the—
more lefty-oriented publications.
He said that he was the commission, you know, 20 years ago was rude to him, and he was going to get redemption.
He was going to find vindication in his treatment by the commission.
We've all tried to understand him.
When I first came on the commission,
I listen to some of his stuff, puts out a newsletter that tries to look like it's an official publication of the department.
And I sat down with him.
We actually met in my office.
He wanted to come and see my office.
It was in another building.
And we spent probably an hour, two hours together.
I said, what does he want?
And he didn't want anything.
I said, what's your opinion on the library?
I'm talking to him by the way.
I'm just curious.
What does he want?
What does he want?
You tell me.
He wants us to follow the law.
It was really funny.
On the restraining order they wanted against us on the secretary of the commission, they asked for us to follow the law.
The judge looked at it and said, I'll grant that restraining order, follow the law.
And they thought they had a great victory, and then the city attorney says, what does that mean?
Can we hire this, move ahead with the hiring of the city librarian and the secretary?
He said, if you think that's following the law, you go ahead and do whatever you want.
And then they were devastated.
I mean, that's the silliness.
It is at this level of absolute petty bullshit.
And what's that all about?
Well, I guess they want you to step down from the library.
I think you've got to look at it.
When you meet Gina, you'll know right now why they can't attack her.
She has no responsibility for anything that's ever happened.
She's a retired...
librarian from Berkeley for 20 years.
And made it clear that she has no agenda beyond six months, so she's really here for that.
She's a former ALA president.
I've read her credentials.
She's fabulous.
She's a real easy-going, you know, she'll be all rumpled the way she dresses, and she's a tough lady, and she's funny, and she's frankly, she's shocking them.
I mean, she's saying things that Dowling said, and they were all over his case.
Card catalog came up at our last commission meeting.
And she looked at them and said, card catalog is just not an efficient, meaningful way to maintain any kind of your collection.
You can't find it.
You have to have card catalogs in all of the different branches.
It is the most costly way imaginable to maintain your collection and to provide access to it.
And it's just not financially feasible in this institution or in any libraries.
As a backup system, you know, we've got it sitting in the basement.
But, you know, she's sitting there making statements that Dowlin said, and they just rolled all over.

And with her, you know, the two or three people that are regulars in the audience, you know, were just sitting and looking at her with wide eyes, and the little union click, which was all over Dowlin on the, you know, on the card catalog issue, just sat there and looked.
They're afraid to say anything to her.
They don't know what to deal with her.
Who are they going to go after then?
Once, Dowlin was the focus.
When Dowlin left, they turned on me.
And then when we brought, then they sort of backed off after a while, because clearly the mayor was not interested.
They were getting nowhere with him.
Then we brought in Gina, who I think has been great.
Now, who picked Gina?
How did you get Gina?
I asked her.
Who was impressed?
I was really impressed.
We were...
I've been trying to work through the backlog.
This was your move, then, to go after Gina?
Yes.
And the commission, in fact, had one of the commissioners here, Charles Aguedis, and I sat for two hours and interviewed Gina before we offered the job, just walking through the issues.
And what's your hope that she will accomplish?
stability and normalcy?
I'm convinced that we will not find a first-rate librarian on a permanent basis to take the system until we show that we are not in the hellhole of libraries on earth.
We get our, you know, address the weeding issue and management, collection management issues.
We address storage issues.
We address
issues around getting materials back on the shelf.
Materials back on the shelf is the number one issue, as far as I'm concerned.
We've gone from the absolute worst, when we had labor fights over the pages, and where we were like six weeks behind in shelving some materials to 72 hours.
That's what we said right now.
It's about 72 hours for all materials.
and they hope to get it to 48.
I just want them to be consistent, set our goal, and then keep it.
I think we've got to do a variety of things to get the library in shape, build what clearly is some continuity here.
We have a reputation of a library that is run, I think, within librarians that I deal with around the country, a library where the union is out of control.
And I think we have to show that that is not the case.
Do you think you have that situation?
I think—I've been involved for nine years.
The union has not always—the union has always been contentious, but I've always found them reasonable to deal with up until the last two years, and the shift in the stewards.
And Kathy Bremer is the chief steward.
And I have found that they were— What's your agenda?
You said political power.
What kind of power?
I mean, I can't even—
chief steward of the librarian.
That's the issue.
You think this is a power grab on her part to actually— You wanted me to be candid.
I'd tell this to her face.
No, I want you to be candid.
I think that's what it's all about.
And you don't think it's about reading collections, folding humanities and literature into one, getting rid of— Who's going to run a library?
They're scared to death of private money.
Because they think private money you can't control.
They don't like volunteers.
Private money being what?
Like a telephone company, for instance?
I mean, that's an issue.
I mean, there is certainly the coincidental circumstance of you're working for this company, which is a major contributor to the library.
Why do you think they're a major contributor to the library?
You tell me.
I don't know.
Because I'm involved.
And I've pushed resources away the library.
So you came before the telephone company, so to speak.
We didn't do squat for the library before I got involved.
I mean, it's also alleged that, you know, the telephone company stands to make thousands of dollars, millions of dollars every time somebody makes a
That it's in your best interest.
I'm telling you what people say.
You've heard this stuff before.
I've heard this stuff before.
I actually went back.
I'm from Massachusetts, so I'm open to hear anything anyone has to say.
Let's just deal with some of these kinds of issues you've got here.
If you don't mind.
I would acknowledge you by asking.
I've had four Ethics Commission violations filed against me in the last year, one by Mr. Hale.
Mr. Hale being who?
I don't know.
Hale is one of the gap lines.
I haven't really talked to all of them, by the way.
One by one of the library staff activists.
It does get tedious after a point, I have to tell you.
Yeah.
So I've had four filed against things, one by one of the gadflies, one signed by one of the union activists, who you probably talked to.
Two others were anonymous.
The Ethics Commission looked at all four of them, and they were all charging that I was doing these illegal things and doing things that I shouldn't be doing within the library.
everything you've heard was in this file.
They found no basis to any of it.
The Ethics Commission of San Francisco.
It's a governmental... It's a governmental body appointed by the mayor that is to look at conflicts of interest between appointed elected officials.
Alleged conflicts of interest.
Alleged conflicts of interest in the city and county of San Francisco.
So I've had four of them filed against me since I've been back on the commission.
Four of them, four times, the commission has found there is no evidence.
When the mayor hired an auditor,
to come in and look at the library.
I said, among the things I'd like you to look at are charges of conflict of interest against me.
She said, I'll add it to the list.

In the audit findings, she came out and said, there have been charges that commission president Steve Coulter has been in a conflict of interest in his position as president of the commission and as also an executive with Pacific Belt.
I find absolutely no basis for any of these charges.
telecommunications department, an agency quite independent, has nothing to do with the library, makes all decisions on telecommunications in this city.
So that's five times.
Five times government agencies have looked at this, and it's still here.
So tell me why I'm still dealing with that if there's not a political agenda that goes beyond this.
Tell me why, if there's not a political agenda, are they hounding Ken Dallin, you know, in his job at San Jose State?
Are they hounding David Price, who was his guy, on the budget when he's back in West Virginia?
Price is a new name for me.
David Price.
He was one of Ken's guys that he hired when I was off the commission.
Do you think Ken Dallin is a man of vision?
I think Ken was really problematic.
I like Ken personally.
I did not hire him.
I thought that he had a broad vision.
I thought it was an impractical one, often, frankly, as we looked at the technology that he wanted to do.
Of the Library of the Future.
I thought the videotape, the one you saw, I gave him the money.
He said he wanted to do a videotape on the Library of the Future.
I said, okay.
I said, here's the money.
Go do it.
You have the robotic voice.
And I saw the goddamn thing, and I looked at it, and I thought, this is terrible.
I asked Ken, what in the hell were you thinking?
I thought it was done here.
Our corporate TV did it.
I asked the woman who had it, I said, do a good job, present his vision.
Because at that point, I'd just come on the commission.
He wanted to put it together, and I thought, well, $25,000, $30,000.
He wanted to do a vision, a videotape that he could show...
basically other techie types, I had thought that it was something we could use in our fundraising.
I saw the tape, and the first thing I said was, you know, Ken, we can't use this.
This is the most cold, insensitive, undesirable picture of the future that I've ever seen.
Well, the woman is a hologram.
I mean, a woman talking who's not real.
So I mean, women would get totally pissed off about that.
I couldn't believe it.
And then the voice, the narrator, is a robotic voice.
Yeah, no, it was a terrible piece.
I said, kid, you can't, your videotape on libraries ought to be just full of kids and exciting programs and history.
I said, you've got kids in there as a little sidelight, about five seconds.
So we never used it.
And the books are in the glass, by the way.
Yeah.
And the type catalog is gathering dust.
It's a relic of fossil.
I said, Jesus Christ, if you're looking to influence people.
Well, but you've got to look at what Ken was.
He saw himself—because I went to a number of ALA and CLA conferences where Ken spoke, because I wanted to see the guy.
And I took part in some conferences myself, just talking about what our emerging vision was for the San Francisco Library and fundraising kind of stuff.
Ken was—saw himself as a prophet way out there, and the difference between
being a prophet who does not have to produce and being a prophet who does, I think is a lot.
And so when he went from the theoretical to the actually having to do it, I think he ran into a lot of problems.
But as a writer, and as someone who wanted to establish a reputation, he was trying to be further out than anybody else on a lot of the stuff.
And that can get you into trouble sometimes.
If you get into a position where you've actually got to produce and
He was not good political.
I think, I thought a lot of his ideas were very intriguing.
I thought he was a nice guy to deal with personally.
The last year and a half that we, the last year and a half, you know, I've been off commission for two years, although I continued to raise money for the library, went on the Library Foundation.
When I came back, the focus was clearly just, I mean, I came back on in mid-January, and we opened in April.
And so we were just trying to put the opening together.
But after that, there was a disconnect from reality.
We had some strong discussions about the directions we were going.
The book shelving problem, for example, the commission had an entirely different view than Ken did on how we had to handle it.
He wanted to go to war with the Union over the pages.
Because there had been three years of discussions about whether we were going to create a new class of employee called shelvers that would be paid less.
Our pages are the highest paid in the United States.
They make between, I don't know, $12 and $15 now, an hour.
And Ken wanted to set up a new category at $7 an hour, and they were called shelvers.
And we needed a lot of shelvers for the NMA Library.
We knew that.
He was going to—he was allowing the books to back up, arguing that'll make the union look bad.
And we said, Ken, anyone's going to look bad is you in the library.
We got in a big fight over the thing.
But at the same time, in June of last year, the charter to the city changed, and the role of commissions changed.
And we went from a commission that oversaw basically everything to a commission that was only policy.
And that—
Ken felt that meant that the commission didn't run the library.
He did.
He was the CEO.
He was the mayor's guy.
We told him, yeah, that's true in some sense, but you're not the mayor's guy.
You're Steinstein's guy, and she hasn't been the mayor for a long time, and you're not appointee of this mayor.
Anyway, he pushed back on us and basically alienated his own commission on him, and then he ran into financial trouble.
So he had to go.
Basically, he had not thought through some of the budget items well at all.
The page issue turned out to be a disaster.
People found it hard to find a lot of materials.
Now, let me come out on his defense.
One labor person that you have talked to came and approached the senior managers and said, you know, books will get back on the shelf a whole lot quicker if you get rid of those volunteers.
You have to assume that there was some sabotage on people wanting him to look as bad as possible to get rid of the guy.
Can— Of course, you have nothing to back that up.
That's just the sense that you have, based on maybe— Comments like that.
—the veiled—the not-so-veiled suggestion that maybe, you know, if you get rid of the volunteers,
As Ken was arguing... Things will improve.
Let me give you some examples.
Ken, when we was talking about the pages at their worst, Kathy Bremer put out a flyer.
She's the chief steward.
I know, by the way.
Yeah, calling for the pages.
It was a call to arms.
Don't let them, you know, kick out our weakest members.
We had 23 pages show up.
I'd listened to all of them in three minutes apiece.
Angry...
at anyone who would threaten them, and a lot of them, in their public testimony.

Because the union over time has taken the pages and allowed a page to go from somebody who just shelves books to someone who can check them out, who can have access to the database, what have you, which is a little bit more like a librarian than a page.
And we have page after page stand up there and talk about, if they have to, they will put books on the shelf.
But primarily they're writers and authors and
They are playwrights.
They are working on their second degrees.
And the commission came away with a point of view that basically this is an angry group of employees, one that thinks they're too good to show books, and probably one.
We talked to some of my other commissioners.
Don't just look at me.
I mean, I'm one of seven.
But I think pages do important work.
You've got to have somebody doing it.
I think we've created a professional class of pages that no other library has done.
New York pays six an hour, and we're paying 15 for our top pages.
And it's, you know, we hired 40 more pages.
The union's position is pages should be full-time, full benefits, protected position.
I think that's the craziest thing I've ever heard in my life.
But if the city is willing to come up with the money for a skewed labor force, then great.
I don't care.
I mean, that's a decision the mayor and the board of supervisors are going to make.
They're imposing these conditions on us.
I just have to sit and look at the budget and wonder, are we so politicized?
Is the union trying to roil up problems so much that it makes so many people angry that you had problems?
I mean, I have had stories of people come and say pages are putting the books in the wrong place intentionally.
They wanted to maximize the pain on Dallin to get rid of him.
So that's in his defense.
I've already told you on the other side, I thought he was his own worst enemy on a lot of stuff and wouldn't listen to the commission.
And we had some real come-to-Jesus private discussions with him.
We're criticized because we didn't do it publicly up until almost the very end.
We had ordered him, the last commission meeting before he left, I had sat in a meeting, and I had absolutely ordered him to meet with the union on these issues.
The rest of the commission concurred that he must do that.
And he gave his presentation on the budget, which was probably the best presentation he's ever done on the budget, the most cohesive I'd ever seen.
And we asked about his union conferring, and he said he hadn't met.
All seven of us at that point were so angry.
We knew it was useless.
We knew that sitting down with Kathy Bremer would accomplish nothing, but he had an obligation to sit down and do it.
And he wouldn't do it.
He refused to deal with them most of his last year.
And it was stupid.
From our position, it was absolutely a kiss of death, because I don't think the rank and file is hostile.
I think most people on the staff are great people.
I think you've got
some troublemakers.
I think this is San Francisco, you know, where everybody, you know, loves a good fight.
I think most of the staff, everything I've heard, is they just want to get on with the job, and they're tired of, you know, this kind of stuff in some of these meetings.
Some of the people are absolutely shocked to find out some of the things, you know, that happen in some of our meetings.
I mean, when you're sitting down there with Kathy Bremer and some of her folks, ask them why they were so opposed to private money.
Why are they so opposed to my
You know, my affinity group center is coming in.
Well, yeah, and, you know, I said to some of these people, I said, you know, I did Paul LeClaire, who's the president of the New York Public Library, who was a friend of mine.
Heard great things about him.
And, you know, he's not a librarian, he's a librarian.
Well, most of the great librarians today aren't librarians.
I mean, Barton is a historian.
Barton is one of the people who got us energized.
Yeah, it's fabulous.
And so Paul said to me, you know how much money I have to raise every week?
He said, pick a number to keep this thing going.
He said, $600,000 a week is what I raise.
You know, that's $30 million a year.
And the New York Public Library, as I said to some of these people, had to realize that's a totally

that's public only in name it's a private totally private institution and arguably the greatest public library in the world it's fabulous it is fabulous so I mean that's not a defense that you know I told you I have an open mind to these things and I'm a book person and I'm a library person but you know is it necessary to keep every copy of the phone book I hope not
You know what I'm saying?
But I think one copy of the phone book is good because you do get demographic information out of the phone book.
You know, we're struggling.
I'm concerned now, but when we had our first chat on the phone, you didn't say we had our problems.
Oh, we do.
Major problems, and you're hoping that they're behind you.
I am concerned about the future.
I mean, is there room for new books down there?
So clearly...

There's going to have to be kind of an aggressive program of weeding and getting— Well, I want to— And we haven't really discussed the sending of the books off to the landfill, which really probably, you know, is easily their most dramatic, you know, of the Nicholson-Bakers story which made this national.
Yeah, that happened about the time I was coming on The Commissioner, maybe it wasn't even on yet, it happened in December.
I came on in mid-January.
I was right in there when that story hit.
Which story?
The dumping of the books.
The dumping of the books.
And it made no sense to me, because they're not supposed to do that.
I mean, that's not what our policy is, that you take books to the dump.
Now, that was the policy under the city when I first came in, when Dowland first came in.
And Dowland, to his credit, went to the board of supervisors and said, I ought to be able to sell books that we don't need anymore, that we need it, or give them away.
They changed the statutes within the city.
At that point, that's all you could do.
You had to declare surplus and of no use, and you tossed it.
So he changed the law in San Francisco.
That stuff, we've got a process that says, you know, the friends can sell it.
You give it to community groups.
We've gone one step further, and, you know, we can give them away to the public now when we have no use for them anywhere else.
But that was a weird one.
And I handled that one wrong coming on the commission.
I made a big mistake on that.
I thought our focus was opening the new main library.
I thought it was an aberration.
I don't know how many were taken to the dump, but it was clearly not policy to do that.
But it happened.
I should have called a public meeting on it and chastised the hell out of some staff and come to the bottom of what happened.
I thought you didn't know about it.
I do about it after the fact.
I mean, it shows up in the paper, and I'm reading the thing and saying, what in the hell is this?
No, but you didn't know about it while it was going on.
No, I didn't know a thing about it.
I talked to the senior library staff.
They tell me they didn't know anything about it either.
So what was Dowling's undoubtedly must have known?
He claims he didn't.
Kathy Page claims she didn't know.
So who was doing it?
Well, I mean, you get into one of these kinds of things.
The argument was that staff was acting in an unauthorized way that got in a panic.
over how to move this stuff.
He closed the old main library in December, and they had to move, pick a number, umpteen million items.
Dowling picked 13 million items, and I've heard a number of items.
If you count everything, there's a lot of stuff.
